'''Dhātus''' (dhä·tōōs), n.pl. ( from [[Sanskrit]] धातु dhātu - layer, stratum, constituent part, ingredient, element, primitive matter<ref>Sanskrit-English Dictionary by Monier-Williams, (c) 1899</ref> ) in [[Ayurveda]], the seven fundamental principles (elements) that support the basic structure (and functioning) of the body.<ref>Jonas: Mosby's Dictionary of Complementary and Alternative Medicine. (c) 2005, Elsevier.</ref>

They consist of:
*Rasa dhatu ([[Lymph]])
*Rakta dhatu ([[Blood]])
*Mamsa dhatu ([[Muscles]])
*Medha dhatu ([[Fat]])
*Asthi dhatu ([[Bone]])
*Majja dhatu (marrow (bone and spinal))
*Shukra dhatu ([[Semen]])<ref>[http://ayurveda.iloveindia.com/ayurveda-fundamentals/dhatu-significance.html Seven Dhatus of Ayurveda]</ref>

Traditional texts often refer to the above as the Seven Dhātus (Saptadhātus). Ojas is known as the eighth Dhātu, or Mahādhātu (superior, or great dhātu).<ref>Dhātus http://www.ayurveda-recipes.com/dhatus.html</ref>

==See also==
[[Dhatu (disambiguation)|Dhātu]] (disambiguation) - a Buddhist technical [[Skandha#Eighteen_Dhātus|term]] or a [[stupa]], [[Pāli]] ''thūpa''.

